#Text=Egyptian military issues ultimatum to Morsi
#Text=Monday , July 1 , 2013

#Text=Today the Egyptian military issued an ultimatum to Mohammed Morsi that gives him 48 hours , until Wednesday , to meet the demands of the hundreds of thousands of people protesting his presidency , by announcing a snap election , resigning , and allowing a provisional government to take over , or they will force a political transition .
#Text=For an institution of state to come and stage a coup against the president , this will not happen .
#Text=Any force that goes against the constitution is a call for sabotage and anarchy .
#Text=— Yasser Hamza , member of the Freedom and Justice Party
#Text=The military said the protests were an " unprecedented " demonstration of the people 's will .
#Text=The ultimatum was issued by an unnamed official on Egyptian state television hours after the Muslim Brotherhood 's headquarters in Cairo was taken over .
#Text=Accompanied by an image of the Egyptian Defense Minister General Abdul Fatah Khalil Al-Sisi , the ultimatum read , "

column3:
_	_	_	_

#Text=If the demands of the people are not met by the expiry of this deadline , the Armed Forces will announce a road-map for the future , and procedures that the Armed Forces will oversee with the participation of all political and national streams , including the youths , who were and still are the real force that ignited their glorious revolution , and without the exclusion of any party  , after which the television channel played patriotic music .

#Text=The military also said it would  not be a party in politics or rule , " and would enforce what the people wanted .

#Text=Image : Jonathan Rashad .
#Text=The Muslim Brotherhood has denounced the ultimatum .

#Text=Yasser Hamza , a member of the Freedom and Justice Party , the political party of the Muslim Brotherhood , said , " For an institution of state to come and stage a coup against the president , this will not happen .

#Text=Late Sunday , the National Salvation Front released a statement telling protesters to  maintain their peaceful [ rallies ] in all the squares and streets and villages and hamlets of the country ... until the last of this dictatorial regime falls " and stated that this has " confirmed the downfall of the regime of Mohamed Morsi and the Muslim Brotherhood " .

column1: #Text=The National Salvation Front , a secular , liberal organization , has endorsed a petition calling for a snap election , started by the grassroots movement Rebel .

#Text=maintain their peaceful [ rallies ] in all the squares and streets and villages and hamlets of the country ... until the last of this dictatorial regime falls — National Salvation Front in " Revolution Statement 1 "
#Text=Protesters argue Morsi since taking power has failed to address political deadlock , economic crises , and personal safety problems .
#Text=Many are angry at the Muslim Brotherhood , which they claim hijacked the Egyptian revolution , seizing authoritarian control and imposing Islamic law .
#Text=The BBC reported some protesters showed anti-American and anti-Israeli sentiment , noting one flag with a picture of Morsi in a Star of David .
#Text=A presidential spokesman , Ihab Fahmi , said people must " unite and listen to the sound of wisdom [ ... ] Political diversity necessitates on all parties to abide by the democratic process " .
#Text=Another spokesman , Omar Amer , said " [ Morsi ] announced to all of Egypt ’s people he made mistakes and that he is in the process of fixing these mistakes [ ... ]
